b"2020 has been a record year for pet adoptions and sales. Demand has been so high for dog and cat companionship, many shelters had waiting lists at one point. But 2019 was a different story...

Dash, a white and tan pit bull, was one of the longest residents at macc. Older pit bulls are often shelter veterans, as many adopters look for small dogs and puppies.

Molly Romine, a State Farm employee and shelter volunteer, knew Dash would make a great addition to someone\xe2\x80\x99s family. That's why she and other volunteers helped organize a 12 Dogs of Christmas adoption push last December. 

The shelter\xe2\x80\x99s 12 longest-term residents were all pit bulls ranging in age from 2 to 10. The team spruced up their kennels with eye-catching decor, gave the doggies holiday makeovers and shared social media posts to gain attention. The shelter also offered stockings full of donated leashes, collars and free training sessions.

\xe2\x80\x9cI worked a couple of hours a night to get these dogs a home for the holidays,\xe2\x80\x9d shared Molly. \xe2\x80\x9cIt was a lot of hard work but it was worth it to see Dash and all the other dogs adopted just before New Year\xe2\x80\x99s Eve!\xe2\x80\x9d

Volunteering has been difficult during COVID-19 due to social distancing and other safety measures, but there are still ways to give back.

\xe2\x80\x9cIf you\xe2\x80\x99re not sure adoption is for you, consider fostering! It\xe2\x80\x99s a short-term commitment with long-term impacts,\xe2\x80\x9d Molly recommends. \xe2\x80\x9cIf you foster a pet, you are giving that animal a much needed respite from the stressful shelter environment. You can also provide the shelter with helpful intel. Maybe the dog is great with kids but scared of car rides. This can really help match the pup with the right family.\xe2\x80\x9d

This #GivingTuesday, reach out to your local animal shelter to find out how you can add a new family member to your home through fostering or adoption. #GoodNeighbor #PetAdoption"

b"Even if you're not there when it happens, a home break-in can shatter your feeling of security. Fortunately, taking these steps can help reduce the risk of a burglary. #GoodNeighbor 

When moving into a new residence, have the locks changed. Consult a good locksmith to make sure you have the right types of locks on your doors and windows.

Secure exterior doors and doors from attached garages by installing quality deadbolt door locks, doorjamb reinforcement, reinforced hinges, security-type door strikes, and strong, properly installed doors and door frames that can't be spread apart.

Secure your windows by installing additional locks and impact-resistant glass on any windows within 42' of a door lock. This will make it more difficult to break the glass, reach in and unlock the lock.

Secure your patio door with a pin-type lock, a key lock or a steel rod inserted into the door channel.

Prune lower branches of trees near your house if they could help a burglar gain access to a second story window.

Set up contact sensors for points of entry, motion detectors or security cameras that can sync to a home monitoring system and be programmed to notify the owner via text, email or phone call when someone enters the residence. #safety #HomeSecurity"

b"Help ensure your family can enjoy a safe and happy Thanksgiving by following these turkey fryer tips. #GoodNeighbor

Keep outdoor fryers off decks, out of garages and a safe distance away from trees and other structures.

Place the fryer on a level surface and avoid moving it once it's in use. Leave 2 feet between the tank and the burner when using a propane-powered fryer.

Follow the manufacturer's instructions to avoid overfilling. Oil can ignite when it makes contact with the burner.

Choose a smaller turkey for frying. A bird that's 8 to 10 pounds is best. Pass on turkeys over 12 pounds.

Make sure the turkey is thawed and dry before cooking. Ice or water can cause flare-ups if mixed with hot oil.

Turn off the burner before lowering the turkey into the oil. Once the turkey is submerged, turn the burner on.

Wear goggles to shield your eyes, use oven mitts to protect your hands and arms, and keep a grease-rated fire extinguisher close by.

Watch the oil temperature carefully. Cooking oil that is heated beyond its smoke point can catch fire. If you notice the oil is smoking, turn the fryer off.

Keep children and pets away from the fryer at all times.

Once finished, carefully remove the pot from the burner, place it on a level surface and cover  to let the oil cool overnight before disposing.

Watch the weather. Never operate a fryer outdoors in rain or snow. #Thanksgiving #ThanksgivingDinner #FriedTurkey"

b"Make your holidays more eco friendly with these tips for reducing waste and conserving energy while you celebrate. #GoodNeighbor

\xe2\x80\xa2 Send electronic invitations and cards to reduce paper waste.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Use natural decorations such as driftwood, dried grasses, winter berries and other natural items.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Eat local. Plan your menu around foods that are grown locally as well as those that are in season.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Lose the disposables. Pull out the china, stemware and cutlery to add a touch of class to your party and reduce the amount of trash.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Opt for LEDs. LED holiday lights use up to 90% less electricity than incandescent bulbs and can last 20 to 30 years. Save even more energy by using a timer to shut lights off automatically.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Try to purchase gifts with the least amount of packaging. If you're shipping presents, create your own packing materials using eco friendly products such as recycled newspaper and shredded paper.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Make your own gift wrap or offer gifts unwrapped. Try using old maps, the Sunday comics, a scarf, or a reusable cloth bag. If gift wrap and ribbons are in good shape, save them to reuse next year.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Recycle. Set out clearly labeled recycling bins at parties so guests can recycle bottles, cans and other items rather than tossing them in the wastebasket.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Give away leftovers. Send extra food home with guests in reusable containers, or freeze leftovers for another day.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Replant your Christmas tree. Or, if you get a fresh tree, turn it into compost or send it through a chipper to make mulch. In some areas of the country, you can even rent a tree.

#EcoFriendly #EnvironmentallyFriendly"

b'Your home appliances can function better and have the potential to last longer with a little regular maintenance. Get started with the items on this list. #GoodNeighbor 

Garbage disposal: Check for blockages and remove with tongs while off, then run the disposal with a deodorizing or cleaning agent like ice cubes and salt, vinegar or frozen citrus.

Dishwasher: Follow manufacturer recommendations for cleaning. Regularly inspect the racks for chips and go over them with special touch-up paint to prevent exposed metal and rust, which can damage your dishes.

Fridge: Clean the interior, exterior and coils according to the manufacturer\xe2\x80\x99s instructions. Regularly inspect the seals on the doors for cracks or breaks.

Microwave: Regularly inspect the interior of the microwave to ensure the seals and coatings are intact.

Washing machine: Look for cracks, weak spots or deformities in the hoses connected to your washing machine to prevent floods or leaks. Replace hoses every five years or as directed by your owners manual.

Dryer: Clean the filter after every use \xe2\x80\x94 no exceptions. Use guidance from the manufacturer to clean out the vent. #HomeImprovement #diy'

b"During the winter, a warm and cozy home does not have to break your budget. Make these simple cost saving adjustments to help keep your family warm and your bill lower. #GoodNeighbor

\xe2\x80\xa2 Adjust your ceiling fan. Hot air gets trapped at the ceiling, but your ceiling fan can help push it downward, which in turn helps your rooms remain warmer. Change the controls so the fan rotates clockwise at a low setting.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Lower your thermostat. Take the setting on your thermostat and lower it at night by 10 degrees, and you could save up to 10 percent on your heating costs.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Lower the temperature on your water heater. Turn down the highest setting on your water heater to 120\xc2\xbaF to trim even more from your utility bills.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Close off unused rooms. Close the vents and the door, too, to reduce the square feet you have to heat. 

\xe2\x80\xa2 Winterize your furnace and water lines.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Run a humidifier. A small humidifier that runs in your main living space can add welcome moisture to the air, increasing your overall comfort level.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Seal your windows, doors and air ducts.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Take advantage of solar rays. Open curtains on south-facing windows during the day to soak up the sun's heat. Draw them at night to help insulate your home. #EnergySaving #MoneySavingTips"

b"October is Crime Prevention Month. Follow these tips to help deter thieves from targeting your vehicle. #GoodNeighbor

\xe2\x80\xa2 Secure your WiFi. If your car has a hotspot, hackers may be able to use it to access your car\xe2\x80\x99s electronic controls.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Track your car. Vehicle tracking systems are widely available and many allow users to track their vehicle's location with mobile apps.

\xe2\x80\xa2 Invest in an anti-theft device. Car alarms, steering wheel locks and kill switches may be enough to persuade thieves to reconsider.

\xe2\x80\xa2 These simple reminders help add a layer of protection to your vehicle. Never leave your car running unattended, always lock your doors and roll up your windows and park in heavily populated, well-lit areas (or in a garage when you can). #crimepreventionmonth  #safety"

b'In honor of National Fire Pup Day, we're celebrating the newly certified teams in class #52 of the State Farm Arson Dog Program! #GoodNeighbor

Arson dogs are trained to work with a human handler and find evidence at fire scenes. The dogs are searching for accelerants such as gas, oil or fuel used to start fires.

The State Farm Arson Dog Program is available to fire departments and law enforcement agencies across the U.S. Since beginning in 1993, the program has placed more than 425 dogs in 46 states, 3 Canadian provinces and the District of Columbia.

Arson crime is one of the most difficult crimes to solve and insurance fraud causes billions of dollars in damage each year. In fact, many police and fire departments are seeing an increase in suspicious fires because of business closures, financial challenges and social disruption.

"Fire investigators should have every tool possible to combat this deadly crime," said Heather Paul, State Farm Arson Dog Program Coordinator. \xe2\x80\x9cThese dogs help fire investigators to do their job. Arson dog teams can quickly locate evidence of accelerants such as gasoline or fuel used to start a fire.\xe2\x80\x9d #DogsOfInstagram #DogsOfInsta #K9'

b"As the leaves change and the days get shorter, take time this autumn to prepare your home for winter.

:red_circle: Heating system maintenance
Change and stock up on air filters for your furnace before the weather gets cold. Call an HVAC contractor to test the heating output and give the system a tune up, as well as checking for hazardous carbon monoxide levels. In extreme cold weather conditions, consider leaving your thermostat at a set level.

:red_circle: Check the fireplace, wood stove, and/or chimney
If you\xe2\x80\x99ll be using the fireplace or wood stove often, call a chimney sweep for an inspection. Seasoned wood is best for fires, as it burns cleaner and longer.

:red_circle: Review home fire safety
Check fire extinguishers and replace them if necessary, and change the batteries in your smoke detectors.

:red_circle: Clean out gutters
It's best to inspect and clean your gutters and downspouts a few times during the fall, especially if there are many trees around your house. If they remain clogged, it could damage the foundation, flood basements, or cause walkways or driveways to become slippery or icy.

:red_circle: Yard maintenance
Rake or blow the leaves into piles and put them at the curb according to your town\xe2\x80\x99s yard waste requirements. When sweeping the leaves off your patio, don't forget to clean, pack up and store any patio furniture for the winter. Disconnect garden hoses and, if practical, use an indoor valve to shut off and drain water from pipes leading to outside faucets.

:red_circle: Test your emergency generator
Make sure you never run the generator in an enclosed space \xe2\x80\x94 like your garage \xe2\x80\x94 as it will present a carbon monoxide hazard.

:red_circle: Inspect your roof
Inspect your roof from a ladder or hire a licensed professional to review the condition of your roof. Look for any wear and tear that might have happened during the previous season\xe2\x80\x99s severe storms. If any shingles are curling, buckling or cracking, replace them. 
#HomeMaintenance #SafetyFirst"

b"A car seat is one of the most important purchases you'll make as a parent. Follow these tips to help keep your family safe. #GoodNeighbor

Read your car seat manual and vehicle manual when installing the seat.

Once you install the seat, you should not be able to move it more than one inch in either direction at the belt path. You can do this by using the seat belt or the LATCH system.

The harness straps must be snug and the chest clip should be at armpit level.

Keep your child rear-facing until at least two, even if they are already in a convertible seat.

Whether your child should move to another seat depends on their height and weight, not age.

All car seats (and all kids under 13) should be correctly buckled in the back seat. #ParentingTips #CarSeat #safety"

b"When curious children climb on furniture or pull on appliance cords, it can lead to accidents. Here are five steps you can take to help mitigate the risk. #GoodNeighbor

1. Mount or anchor televisions to the wall or sturdy furniture designed to hold it.

2. Don't place tempting items like candy, toys or remotes on top of large furniture or high shelves.

3. Use wall brackets or anchors for heavy and tall items.

4. Tuck cords away to prevent children from tripping or pulling electronics down.

5. Check your stove's stability and add brackets as a precaution. #parenting #safety"

b"While open windows may help keep your house feeling fresh, breezy and cool, they can also create a safety concern. If you have young children in your home, help prevent tragic falls with these tips. #GoodNeighbor

Install window safety devices on all windows \xe2\x80\x94 even on the first floor.

Close and lock all windows when you\xe2\x80\x99re not in the room.

Don't open windows more than four inches. This prevents small children from being able to squeeze through.

Don't assume a screen makes the window safe. Screens aren't strong enough to hold even a small child.

Move furniture that kids might climb on away from windows. #safety #parenting"

b'In honor of #NationalDogDay, we're sharing tips to help you and your furry friends stay safe during this time of social distancing and sheltering at home. #GoodNeighbor

Create a den-like space or safe area in your home that's a "dog only" zone. This can be a dog crate where the door always remains open or a quiet location that your dog can go when they need some space.

Supervise small children around any dog. You can use baby gates to keep dogs and kids separated if you can\xe2\x80\x99t actively supervise them. This can help keep everyone safe and avoid bites.

Teach your dog some new skills! If you need the help of a trainer, many now offer virtual consultations.

Be consistent. It can be confusing and frustrating for your dog if one member of the family allows them to get on the sofa but another punishes them when they do. Consistency makes learning easier and will give your dog the confidence they need to be successful in their environment.

Exercise and food-puzzle games provide physical and mental stimulation for dogs of all ages and is especially beneficial for dogs that are nervous or anxious. Solving puzzles can be intrinsically rewarding.

Give your dog a treasure hunt! This exercise allows your dog to use their bionic nose. Ask your dog to stay while you hide treats around the home. If your dog hasn't played this game before, start by placing them in plain sight to get them used to the idea. #dogs #pets'

b"In hard times, an emergency fund can mean everything. If you're able, use these tips to help set aside funds for the future. #GoodNeighbor

:triangular_flag: Set an emergency fund goal. It should equal about three to six months of living expenses.

:triangular_flag: Set up a monthly goal for your emergency fund. Even if it\xe2\x80\x99s a small amount, starting today may make a big impact on your savings.

:triangular_flag: Open a separate emergency fund account, and make your first deposit \xe2\x80\x94 even if it\xe2\x80\x99s a very small one.
 
:triangular_flag: Find budget areas to trim. Take a look at spending categories to see if you can trim a few things out and give a quick boost to savings instead. 

:triangular_flag: Put a portion of unexpected cash in your emergency fund. That may mean bonus money, a tax refund, or even small proceeds from selling something you own.

:triangular_flag: If you withdraw from your emergency fund, come up with a plan to replace the money.

:triangular_flag: Remember \xe2\x80\x94 it\xe2\x80\x99s OK to start small, but most importantly, just start. #budgeting #savings"

b"Moving to a new state? Make note of these potential differences to help avoid unexpected costs. #GoodNeighbor

Driving and car differences:
Learn what type of weather you might encounter in your new location and the warning signs and safety measures for your new state (like a tornado siren or a hurricane evacuation plan).

Tinted car windows are legal in some states, but could get you a citation in others.

Every state has slightly different highway terms and traffic laws. Take time to learn your state's rules of the road.

Home differences:
Heating and AC costs may vary by location. Make a new plan for your bills and adjust your budget or your temperature settings after the move.

Talk with your local State Farm agent about different policy additions available because of your new location, like endorsements for sinkholes, earthquakes, backup of sewer and drain, and others.

Take a look at the crime rate in your new location, and find out if there are additional safety features on your new home, like an alarm.

Be sure to contact your insurance company to update your policies. #tips #moving"

b"With many students across the U.S. participating in virtual learning this fall, it's important to talk through online safety reminders as a family. Start with these tips. #GoodNeighbor

Keep your personal information personal. Discuss what's considered personal info and why it should be kept private. This may include: full name, phone number, financial information, school name and SSN.

Watch for quizzes that ask specific questions like: name of your first pet, street where you grew up and mother\xe2\x80\x99s maiden name. As innocent as some quizzes seem, they may be phishing for answers to commonly used security questions on accounts.

Talk about the privacy settings. Make sure your children have strict privacy settings enabled to protect their photos and updates from strangers. Consider available monitoring services and apps that help keep parents in the loop.

Review what cyberbullying means. Teach your kids not to post embarrassing photos, send mean texts or spread hurtful rumors through electronics, and to immediately report any cyberbullying they see. #safety #OnlineLearning #parenting"

Consider installing a whole-house dehumidifier. #home #summer #tips'

b'Do you know the common signs of a tax scam? Here are some red flags to look out for:

:triangular_flag: Requests for personal or financial information, such as your Social Security number and bank or credit card account numbers

:triangular_flag: Threats that suggest consequences for not responding to the email

:triangular_flag: Incorrect grammar, spelling or phrasing, especially when referencing the IRS or other government agencies

:triangular_flag: Links to inaccurate URLs

:triangular_flag: Emails claiming to be from the IRS

:triangular_flag: Websites that ask for personal or financial information in order to receive a refund

b"Help your family enjoy an injury-free 4th of July celebration with these safety reminders. #GoodNeighbor

Check your state's fireworks laws, only buy legal fireworks and make sure to store them in a cool, dry place. If fireworks are packaged in brown paper, they\xe2\x80\x99re likely made for professional displays (and more dangerous).

Use fireworks in an outdoor location that's a safe distance from homes, structures and anything else that could catch on fire.

Make sure your audience is a safe distance from where the fireworks are being lit.

Keep pets indoors. The sound of fireworks can scare animals and cause them to run away. More animals go missing during the July 4th holiday than any other time of year. #safety #family #4thOfJuly"

b"In the last two years, wildfires have claimed more than 100 lives and over $25 billion in property damage. Follow these recommendations from @nfpadotorg to help reduce the risk of wildfires by taking action around your home. :house: #GoodNeighbor

Remove pine needles and dry leaves within a minimum of 3 to 5 feet from the foundation of your house.

Clean pine needles from the roof and gutters.

Get out your measuring tape and see how close wood piles are located to your home. If they're closer than 30 feet, move them further away from structures.

Sweep porches and decks to clear them of leaves and pine needles. Don't forget to rake under decks, porches, sheds and play structures.

Mow grasses to a height of four inches or less.

Remove items stored under decks and porches and relocate them to a storage shed or garage. #WildfirePrepDay #safety"

b'A pet can be a wonderful addition to your family. In honor of National Dog Bite Prevention week, take a look at some important traits of responsible dog ownership, provided by @avmavets. #preventdogbites

Commit :paw_prints:
Select a pet that's suited to your home and lifestyle and commit to the relationship for the life of your pet(s). Stay with your dog when he or she interacts with new people, and don\xe2\x80\x99t force people to interact with your dog if they appear reluctant, uninterested or afraid.

Invest :dog:
Recognize that pet ownership requires an investment of time and money. Make sure your pet receives preventive health care (vaccinations, parasite control, etc.), as well as care for any illnesses or injuries.

Obey :bone:
Obey all local ordinances, including licensing, leash requirements and noise control. Use a leash in public to ensure you can control your dog and to show others that you are in control of your dog. Train your dog basic commands like "sit," "stay," "no," and "come" to help your pet understand what's expected of them.

Identify :dog_face:
Make sure your pet is properly identified (i.e., tags, microchips, or tattoos) and keep its registration up-to-date.

Prepare :poodle:
Prepare for an emergency or disaster, including assembling an evacuation kit. Make alternate arrangements if you can no longer provide care for your pet. #petsofinstagram'

b"Spring is here! In addition to what you're doing inside, consider completing outdoor home maintenance tasks while sheltering at home. :blossom: #GoodNeighbor

Clean out leaves and other debris that have collected in your gutters and downspouts. Then check to make sure the gutters are safely attached and not leaking. Make sure the downspouts are positioned to direct water away from your home's foundation.

Inspect the foundation around your house. Seal cracks or imperfections and look for low areas in the yard near the foundation that might pool water during a heavy rain. Level these yard depressions by filling them with compacted soil.

Inspect your patio deck for stains, discolorations or warping. If you find any, consider resealing it.

Prep the soil in your garden for new growth. Rake beds of leaves and other leftover winter debris. Use a hoe to churn and loosen the soil and mix in compost for nutrients. If you'll be planting new seeds, follow the instructions provided on the seed packet. #spring #home #tips"

b"Spring is here! In addition to your regular spring cleaning, consider adding these maintenance tasks to your to-do list while you shelter at home. :house_with_garden: #GoodNeighbor

Look around the base of your water heater for evidence of leaks. The average lifespan of a water heater is 8-12 years. If your water heater is over 5 years old, it should be checked monthly for any leakage or rusting at the bottom.

Check your attic for signs of a roof leak. Inspect the underside of the roof and the insulation closely for any discoloration, deterioration or dirt stains.

Check the basement walls, floor and trim for water stains or signs of seepage through the foundation. Keep a close eye on your sump pump, making sure it's still in good working order and has a battery backup if necessary. #spring #home #tips"

b'An empty house is an easy target for burglars, so don't advertise your absence. If your family plans to take a winter vacation, take measures to protect your home while you're away. Here are some helpful tips. :airplane_selector: :beach_with_umbrella_selector: :houses_selector: Have your mail held and stop newspaper deliveries. The post office can hold your mail until you return or forward it to your winter location.

Secure windows and doors. Help keep your home untouched by installing secure locks on all windows and doors.

Time bright outdoor lights to turn on at sundown. Make it appear like someone's home by  using lights on random timers.

Unplug unnecessary appliances. Unplugging TVs, coffee makers and small appliances helps protect against electrical fires or power surges.

Hide the "hide-a-way" key and disable remote key entries. You won't be needing them while you are away.

Enlist help from your neighbors. Ask a trusted neighbor to monitor your property while you're away, collect any flyers that are left on your door and park their car in your driveway periodically.

Hire a snow removal service to take care of your sidewalk and driveway while you're away.

Consider using DIY home security or alarm services. Some apps connect to your home security system and alert you of changes. Others connect your mobile phone with a security camera or webcam to provide remote surveillance.

Turn off the water to washing machines and dishwashers to avoid them leaking. Also, ensure your garden hose is detached.

Create a home inventory. A home inventory can simplify filing an insurance claim if a robbery or accident does happen while you are away. #vacation #tips'

b"Freezing temps can lead to costly property damage. Here are four ways you can help protect your home during a cold snap. :house:

1. Let warm water drip overnight, preferably from a faucet near an outside wall.

2. Open cabinet doors to allow heat to get to un-insulated pipes under sinks and appliances near exterior walls.

3. Keep your thermostat set at the same temperature both day and night.

4. Insulate pipes in your home's crawl spaces and attic, even if you live in a climate where freezing is uncommon. #winter #home #coldweather"

b'Snow on the roof may look pretty, but too much can cause structural damage. Keep the following tips in mind when removing snow build-up from your roof. :snowman_without_snow::house:
\xe2\x80\xa2
:check_box_with_check: Hire a professional. A person who does this work regularly should know the best techniques and likely be insured.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:check_box_with_check: Never work alone. Always have someone with you in case you slip or have an emergency.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:check_box_with_check: Clear the area. The ladder up to your roof should be positioned on solid ground. Also, make sure the rungs are clear of ice and snow before you climb.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:check_box_with_check: Secure yourself. If possible, use a strap or belt to anchor yourself to something strong, like a chimney.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:check_box_with_check: Avoid shingle damage. Stay away from picks, hammers or other sharp tools to clear snow and ice.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:check_box_with_check: Use the right tools. If you have a one-story or flat-roofed house, invest in a snow rake. These long-handled tools with plastic blades can help you gently pull snow from the edge of the roof line. #tips #snow #winter'

b':snowflake_selector::house::snowman_selector: No matter where you live, winter can signal a dip in temperatures and the possibility of unpredictable weather, including inches of snow and dangerous ice. Here are some helpful tips:
:check_mark:
Have your furnace inspected. Since your heating system will probably be running constantly throughout the winter, you should have it inspected annually to help it run efficiently and prevent CO2 from entering your home. Also, remember to change out your HVAC filters every month.
:check_mark:
Inspect the insulation in your attic and crawlspaces. Warm air rises and leaves the house through the roof, so you should focus on insulation in your ceilings. Insulating the crawlspaces will help keep your floors warm. :check_mark:
Seal potential leaks. Seal areas around recessed lights, the attic hatch, and plumbing vents that may be allowing warm air from the living space below to enter the attic.
:check_mark:
Apply weather stripping. Add weather stripping to doors and caulk window gaps. Make sure all windows are locked to keep out as much cold air as possible.
:check_mark:
Use a fireplace. Schedule an inspection and service by a professional to make sure your chimney is clear of debris and make sure your damper opens, closes and seals tightly.
:check_mark:
Insulate pipes. Pipes located in attics, crawl spaces, basements and near outer walls can be susceptible to freezing in extreme temperatures. When the forecast calls for unusually cold temperatures, let water drip from hot and cold faucets overnight and keep a cabinet door open in places like below sinks.'

b':snowflake_selector::house::snowman_selector:Help ensure that your home furnace runs smoothly and efficiently.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Staying cool, keeping warm: Those are the two essential functions of your furnace. But how do you judge when your furnace is nearing the end of its life or when it just needs a little TLC? And what steps can you take to make sure your furnace can do its job?
\xe2\x80\xa2
Use these tips and essential pieces of home furnace maintenance information to find out:
\xe2\x80\xa2
:white_heavy_check_mark: Filter
Check it monthly and replace when suggested (or earlier, if needed). A clogged, dirty filter makes it harder for a furnace to do its job.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:white_heavy_check_mark: Ducts and vents
Your ducts should be securely fastened together, and vents should be clear of debris or dust. Vacuum and dust your home regularly to keep dirt out of air ducts. If your furnace uses a combustion air duct to pull in air from the outside, make sure nothing blocks the outdoor vent such as shrubs or debris.
\xe2\x80\xa2
:white_heavy_check_mark: Service
Schedule service calls as suggested in your owner\xe2\x80\x99s manual or annually. The serviceperson can help you keep tabs on any issues with the condition or function of your furnace.'

b"Whether it's a dog, cat, bird or guinea pig, adding a new pet to your family means more than giving them food and attention \xe2\x80\x93 safety needs to be a top priority, too. :parrot::cat::hamster_face::rabbit: Help turn your home into a safe, animal-friendly environment with these tips.

Living Space: Take a look at everything from your pet's perspective. Common household items like air fresheners, houseplants and game board pieces can pose pet safety risks. Keep storage closed with childproof locks.

Bathroom: Keep toilet bowls securely latched to protect animals from drowning or potential poisoning. Limit the cleaning and beauty products you keep under the sink or on your vanity as they can be harmful to pets if ingested.

Kitchen: Cats and birds can easily get to food on top shelves, so watch for choking hazards. Seal open snack bags in storage containers, make sure lids shut securely and close cabinet doors to prevent unwanted rummaging. Keep counters and sinks free of dirty dishes or food, which can also attract pets.

Other Spaces: Bedrooms, offices and laundry rooms shouldn't be overlooked. Declutter any clothing, shoes or accessories that you store outside your closet. Do a daily check-in to limit the number of trinkets and laundry items that are lying around. #pets #petsofinstagram"

b"Many drivers are unaware of the slippery winter road culprit: black ice. Take a look at warning signs and ways to react before you get on the road.

Warning signs :warning_selector:
\xe2\x80\xa2
Look for the absence of water spray from cars ahead on a seemingly wet road.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Pay attention to cars suddenly swerving or skidding and cars or tire tracks headed off the road.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Be prepared for unexpected brake lights ahead of you.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Look for shiny surfaces next to a dull black roadway.

Ways to react :oncoming_automobile:
\xe2\x80\xa2
Stay calm, avoid making sudden moves or turning the wheel. Lift your foot off the accelerator and glide across the ice in a straight line until you find traction.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Shift. If possible, slowly shift to a lower gear for added control.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Brake wisely. If you begin to skid, firmly press on your brakes to activate the anti-lock brake system (ABS). If you don't have ABS, pump the brakes gently.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Avoid spinout. If your front end is sliding, steer in the opposite direction of the skid; if the back end is sliding, steer in the same direction.
\xe2\x80\xa2
Look toward where you want to go. If you look where you think you might crash, then you might inadvertently veer the car in that direction."

b"When it comes to winter driving, there are some holiday lights you need to avoid. Make sure your tires are properly inflated. Here's some other helpful info: :automobile:
Swap out regular tires for winter tires. Snow or not, if you live in an area where temperatures regularly fall below 45 degrees, winter tires are recommended. They're made to give you better traction while turning or stopping on cold pavement.
:magnifying_glass_tilted_right:
Check tire pressure weekly. Driving on underinflated tires can cause them to wear down prematurely and lose traction on icy or slippery surfaces. Your tires lose a pound of pressure with every 10-degree drop in temperature.
:fuel_pump:
Keep your fuel tank half full. During winter weather, it's a good idea to keep at least half a tank of fuel in the vehicle in the event of an emergency or if you get stuck in the snow and need to wait for rescue. For longer road trips, plan stops for gas in advance.
:shield_selector:
Add a protective layer. A coat of polymer wax can create a barrier against road salt, grime, snow, sleet and more. Couple that with high-pressure car washes after winter storms to rinse away buildup in hard-to-reach areas such as wheels, wheel wells and underbody.
:penguin:
Protect your windshield wipers. If you park outdoors, leave the wipers in the raised position to prevent them from freezing to the windshield. Never use your wiper blades to remove ice, snow or frost from the windshield; use an ice scraper instead. st8.fm/checkpressure"
